    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Core vocabulary: Compensating control (alternative safeguard providing equivalent protection per NIST SP 800-53r5); Primary control (recommended baseline control); Equivalency (comparable risk mitigation). Purpose: Used when primary controls are infeasible, cost-prohibitive, or inadequate.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Key relationships: Part of risk mitigation strategies; Aligned with standards like NIST SP 800-53 (defines compensating controls), NIST CSF (Detect/Respond functions), PCI-DSS. Examples: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) via biometrics + logging instead of hardware tokens.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step process: 1) Assess primary control infeasibility via risk analysis; 2) Identify alternative controls; 3) Validate equivalency (risk reduction comparison); 4) Implement, document (including rationale, monitoring plan), and obtain approval.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Holistic application: Integrate with risk frameworks (NIST 800-39); Optimize via continuous monitoring and audits; Cross-domain links (compliance like PCI-DSS, optimization in cloud/legacy environments); Evolve to primary controls over time.</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
